## Header Behavior

The provider treats `headers` and `custom_headers` as mutually exclusive inputs.

- If `headers` is configured, the provider sends only `headers` to the API and suppresses `custom_headers` in Terraform state.
- If `custom_headers` is configured, the provider sends only `custom_headers` to the API and suppresses `headers` in Terraform state.
- If both are configured at the same time, Terraform returns an error asking you to choose a single source of truth.

> **Recommendation:** Prefer `custom_headers` for new configurations. It provides finer-grained control by letting you scope headers to `root` (initial request only), `all` (every request), or specific `domains`, matching the options available in the ThousandEyes UI. The `headers` attribute is supported for backward compatibility.

Use `headers` when you want to manage request headers as `"Name: value"` strings:

```terraform
resource "thousandeyes_http_server" "example" {
  test_name = "Example HTTP Server"
  url       = "https://example.com"
  interval  = 300
  agents    = ["1234"]

  headers = [
    "Content-Type: application/json",
    "X-TE-Test: upgrade-full",
  ]
}
```

Use `custom_headers` when you need the structured `root`, `all`, or `domains` maps:

```terraform
resource "thousandeyes_http_server" "example" {
  test_name = "Example HTTP Server"
  url       = "https://example.com"
  interval  = 300
  agents    = ["1234"]

  custom_headers {
    root = {
      Content-Type = "application/json"
      X-TE-Test    = "upgrade-full"
    }
  }
}
```

The provider also stores a read-only `header_source_mode` value in state. This is provider bookkeeping used to remember which field is authoritative across refreshes, because the ThousandEyes API can mirror header data between `headers` and `custom_headers`. You may see a one-time planned change for `header_source_mode` when switching an existing resource from one mode to the other. After that transition is applied, subsequent plans should be stable.

